International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Netherlands (North Brabant): mink, further spread, control
[2] Denmark (North Jutland): mink, control measures mitigated

******
[1] Netherlands (North Brabant): mink, further spread, control
Date: Mon 6 Jul 2020
Source: Dutch ministries of Health and of Agriculture, press release [in Dutch, trans., edited]
https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/actueel/nieuws/2020/07/06/bevestiging-van-besmetting-covid-19-bij-nertsenbedrijf-gemert


In Gemert [North Brabant], the infection was officially established at the mink farm where SARS-CoV-2 had previously been suspected. The farm has 12 000 dams. The contamination has been revealed through the early warning monitoring system with which animals are tested weekly for the virus. Another farm was found infected a day earlier.

In total, 20 mink farms in the Netherlands have now been declared infected. All animals were culled at the 18 farms where SARS-CoV-2 has previously been established. The last 2 locations, the 19th and 20th companies, mentioned above, will follow today [6 Jul 2020].

The Cabinet has already taken measures for all fur animal farms in the Netherlands, such as a national ban on mink transport, a visitor ban in stables, and a strict hygiene protocol, to prevent further spread and to prevent SARS-CoV-2 from passing from mink to humans, which plausibly happened in 2 farms.

It is important to emphasize once again that employees with COVID-19 phenomena do not come into contact with minks, do not enter a mink stable, and have themselves tested.

The government is working on a stop scheme according to which mink companies can voluntarily terminate their business operations in the short term. In 2024, mink farms will stop their activities in accordance with the legal prohibition.

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
Gut Laach, D-52385 Nideggen
